  "summary": {
    "as": "Introduced in Senate",
    "asOf": "2018-11-29",
    "date": "2019-08-21T22:39:15Z",
    "text": "Closing the Law Enforcement Consent Loophole Act of 2018\n\nThis bill amends the federal criminal code to make it unlawful for a federal law enforcement officer to engage in a sexual act with an individual who is under arrest, in detention, or in custody.\n\nConsent is not a defense to prosecution for unlawful conduct. A violator is subject to criminal penalties\u2014a fine, a prison term of up to 15 years, or both.\n\nAdditionally, the bill authorizes the Department of Justice to make grants to states that have in effect similar laws. Grants must be used for the same purposes as formula grants under the STOP Violence Against Women Program and the Sexual Assault Services Program."
  },
